      "most_relevant": [
        {
          "username": "Dan Able",
          "rating": 2,
          "contributor_id": "116578184319828835939",
          "user_review_count": 2,
          "user_photo_count": 0,
          "user_thumbnail": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocLuwjbCT8QWGn6tgWzsJD1zNbxPWM0RwGcHfYFoy2zixcOSag=s120-c-rp-mo-br100",
          "description": "Honestly, I would think very carefully before committing to treatment or surgery at this hospital. As a family member who had a parent there for an extended period, I can say that, in hindsight, we likely would not make the same decision again.\n\nSome of the nurses were excellent, but others fell short. The primary physician came across as cold and impersonal, and once it became clear that the treatment trial was not working, their level of engagement noticeably declined. Instead of continuing to see the patient regularly, care was largely handed off to residents.\n\nOver time, I also got the sense that some staff preferred the patient remain in bed rather than being assisted into a chair, likely due to staffing and workload constraints. This was particularly troubling to observe.\n\nI understand that cancer is an incredibly difficult diagnosis, and no process is easy\u2014but, truthfully, MSK did not make the experience any easier for either the patient or the family. The transition from hospital care to hospice at home was especially stressful and did not feel well-coordinated.\n\nThe caseload for hospital staff also appears to be quite high, which likely contributes to long wait times and, at times, lackluster follow-up. I\u2019ll never forget the overcrowded on-site ER, where patients often waited hours just to get a bed and be admitted.\n\nAdditionally, the facility itself feels old and outdated. There is little to no space for families on the hospital floors\u2014no lounges or designated areas to sit\u2014while the limited available spaces appeared to be primarily used  by staff.",
          "link": "https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sCi9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT2tzM1QwMUdMV0ZrVTNnNVdFRTNZa1JmVEZWZlJsRRAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x2016bdf87e63c0a9!3m1!1s2@1:CAIQACodChtycF9oOks3T01GLWFkU3g5WEE3YkRfTFVfRlE%7C%7C?hl=en",
          "date": "3 months ago",
          "date_iso8601": "2026-03-19T03:49:13+00:00"
        },
        {
          "username": "Shamim Riaj",
          "rating": 5,
          "contributor_id": "101239138351385799213",
          "user_review_count": 6,
          "user_photo_count": 0,
          "user_thumbnail": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjXOloAAHO5xkkd29hsxi_l7CPAyGvTt-P5yicb9r6Dq2seyWs3ZCA=s120-c-rp-mo-br100",
          "description": "MSKCC is one of the best in the nation when it comes to cancer care. Because of that we tend to have a high expectation but the reality is different for each patient. Depending on the type of cancer, stage of the cancer, age, health condition etc. outcome for each patient varies. Some will make it through; some will fall victim of the disease. At the end of the day no one wants to lose their loved one doesn\u2019t matter if it is in MSKCC or other cancer hospitals.\n\nI have seen patients getting cancer cares in other hospitals here in NYC areas vs. MSKCC. From my personal experience I have to say that MSKCC really outperformed in two areas:\n\n1.\tPersonalized patient care\n2.\tTheir cutting-edge technology and innovations\n\nPatients will have a better chance if you get care at MSKCC but that doesn\u2019t mean it applies to every patient. You just have to take your chances and hope for the best. At one point, cancer used to be a death sentence and still the same for certain cancers but we came far enough to learn more about this disease, formulate new treatments to prolong life and even cure some cancer types which weren\u2019t possible earlier. Wait another 10-15 years and I am 100% certain that there will be more cures and people will live longer than they are today with this disease. Before we get to that point, many lives will perish. It is upsetting but that\u2019s the fact we need to accept.",
          "link": "https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sCi9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT25GdU5sZGFUSFpQYXpSSVZXcDJiR3RaTVdKRk5VRRAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x2016bdf87e63c0a9!3m1!1s2@1:CAIQACodChtycF9oOnFuNldaTHZPazRIVWp2bGtZMWJFNUE%7C%7C?hl=en",
          "date": "6 months ago",
          "date_iso8601": "2025-12-06T06:47:23+00:00"
        },
        {
          "username": "bfsa members",
          "rating": 3,
          "contributor_id": "117691936317263795394",
          "user_review_count": 1,
          "user_photo_count": 0,
          "user_thumbnail": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocIU-EPlYDD7wi9eb1ZIulxKEh99yzd3yrJ4R6LJnGR1qaJRDw=s120-c-rp-mo-br100",
          "description": "Excellent hospital for care. The staff is not friendly at all. The don\u2019t speak when walking into the room. When you do go and ask a question they seem uninterested. I purchased a coffee when I was in the cafeteria the cashier didn\u2019t say a word not even my total. The nurses are worse. Visited a patient in ICU the nurse walked in 3 different times before I had to ask what her name was because she walked in like I wasn\u2019t sitting there. Please work on having staff being more friendly in a not so customer centric environment the patients for sure don\u2019t want to be here and neither does their loved ones",
          "link": "https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sCi9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT2sxSE5GSXpWeTFxZGpKM1NpMVpVbEU0WlhoNVZtYxAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x2016bdf87e63c0a9!3m1!1s2@1:CAIQACodChtycF9oOk1HNFIzVy1qdjJ3Si1ZUlE4ZXh5Vmc%7C%7C?hl=en",
          "date": "2 months ago",
          "date_iso8601": "2026-04-03T00:03:14+00:00"
        },
        {
          "username": "Chrissy",
          "rating": 1,
          "contributor_id": "108163512171750028170",
          "user_review_count": 30,
          "user_photo_count": 2,
          "user_thumbnail": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjXO7BJT_dj_aEAxILmSWnI3fi2SHTyVUEEj5Cswdx9cYhcw01UrJQ=s120-c-rp-mo-ba12-br100",
          "description": "Between spending hours of speaking to ink-take and filling out online forms I was scheduled for an appt. I was scheduled to come in. Approx 3 hour drive. I wait for well over 2 hours and was seen by a very kind nurse. Then the Doctor came in. She arrogantly told me (like it was my fault) that she was not the doctor for me. She had no idea why I was booked with her. I mean what do you do in a situation like that, she asked me few questions and stated that I could come in tomorrow for a CT \u201cbut that\u2019s wasn\u2019t going to happen today\u201d I never felt so stupid in all my life. She also stated to me \u201cyou don\u2019t even want what some of these patients have\u201d I\u2019m sorry my cancer wasn\u2019t bad enough for you to care. Shame on you. And the follow up apology phone call like a month later made me sick. \u201cIt was a training error\u201d well you better train you facility to NOT BILL MY INSURANCE\u2026.money grab!!!!! How could you even trust a place like this???? When I think about my experience I literally cry.",
          "link": "https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sCi9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT210YWRISlJjbkpZZEc5WlZtUTROWEpOYkVwSGFuYxAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x2016bdf87e63c0a9!3m1!1s2@1:CAIQACodChtycF9oOmtadHJRcnJYdG9ZVmQ4NXJNbEpHanc%7C%7C?hl=en",
          "date": "3 months ago",
          "date_iso8601": "2026-03-10T18:59:51+00:00"
        },
        {
          "username": "Rhonda Guariniello",
          "rating": 5,
          "contributor_id": "110974044664012410660",
          "user_review_count": 11,
          "user_photo_count": 0,
          "user_thumbnail": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocJ_iD5IVU7aiPG752W1EpkxHsFHqdarWLz39wkz8nJZP04UVQ=s120-c-rp-mo-br100",
          "description": "This weekend I\u2019m riding in Cycle for Survival with deep gratitude for my incredible doctors at MSK, Dr. Segal and Dr. Karagkounis. Your expertise, compassion, and unwavering support have carried me through some very hard moments. I ride in honor of you and all you do for your patients every single day. Thank you for giving me strength, hope, and confidence. \ud83d\udc9b\ud83d\udeb4\u200d\u2640\ufe0f",
          "link": "https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sCi9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT2xSeWJscEpWRzFOWm10aFRHdERjM1Y0VFdkekxVRRAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x2016bdf87e63c0a9!3m1!1s2@1:CAIQACodChtycF9oOlRyblpJVG1NZmthTGtDc3V4TWdzLUE%7C%7C?hl=en",
          "date": "4 months ago",
          "date_iso8601": "2026-02-05T16:12:51+00:00"
        },
        {
          "username": "Justin McManus",
          "rating": 1,
          "contributor_id": "117572298276158051685",
          "user_review_count": 7,
          "user_photo_count": 2,
          "user_thumbnail": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocLyJwTIphwaZJFpuB6debSuhrTfFiTGvFa2OPsZnahVxhfgFShw=s120-c-rp-mo-br100",
          "description": "Incredibly disappointed, and quite frankly appalled by the way my father (a stage 4 pancreatic cancer patient) was treated. After driving from northern CT to the city and arriving around 11:15am for a 12:30pm appointment, he waited for an hour and a half in the waiting room and an additional hour and a half in his exam room.\n\nThe wait in and of itself aren't necessarily the problem; doctors and other clinical staff are slammed, understaffed, and stretched thin. However, the oncologist did not once acknowledge the wait or thank my father for his patience. Additionally, no labs were taken and the reason for the visit (to discuss clinical trials) resulted in just a few minutes wherein the doctor explained that there were in fact no trials available, and my father was free to go. 12 hours in and out of the city,  no compassionate care from the providers, and a scheduled appointment that could easily have been a phone call. Deeply sad.",
          "link": "https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sCi9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT2s4eVZXTnlXbVkxUldsR1lqVTJSREowVVVSelNGRRAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x2016bdf87e63c0a9!3m1!1s2@1:CAIQACodChtycF9oOk8yVWNyWmY1RWlGYjU2RDJ0UURzSFE%7C%7C?hl=en",
          "date": "8 months ago",
